There are a few moons in the solar system that are large enough to change their dwarf planet's orbit significantly. 
-> The Moon (Luna)
-> Charon (Moon of Pluto)

The centre of mass between the Earth and Luna is 1700 km below sea level, which is a lot farther away from Earth's centre. This makes Earth and the Moon to both 
orbit the centre of mass of the binary dwarf planet system. 
The Pluto-Charon system is even more extreme, where the centre of mass lies outside Pluto, about 2163 km from Pluto's centre. 
We can conclude that Charon is a dwarf planet, and the moon is uncomfortably close to a dwarf planet and might even be one based on the definition. 
